minimal-linux-net

1. parent system pre-setup (fyi)

64-bit debian linux on /dev/sda (latest-stable-version)
previously built minimal-linux-new (ex. on /dev/sda7 at /mnt/sda7)
internet connection

2. within the parent system open a terminal and become su

3. mount the partition where minimal-linux-new exists

mount -t ext4 /dev/sda7 /mnt/sda7

4. add /mnt/sda7/etc/hostname

cat > /mnt/sda7/etc/hostname << 'done'
localhost
done

5. add /mnt/sda7/etc/hosts

cat > /mnt/sda7/etc/hosts << 'done'
127.0.0.1 localhost
done

6. add /mnt/sda7/etc/nsswitch.conf

cat > /mnt/sda7/etc/nsswitch.conf << 'done'
hosts: files dns
done

7. add /mnt/sda7/etc/resolv.conf

cat > /mnt/sda7/etc/resolv.conf << 'done'
nameserver 1.1.1.1 1.0.0.1
done

8. obtain default route information for your system

ip route show (**sample output information**)

	default via 192.168.0.1 dev eth0
	192.168.0.0/24 dev eth0 scope link  src 192.168.0.2

9. create a script called eth0on using your output information

mkdir /mnt/sda7/var/tmp
cat > /mnt/sda7/var/tmp/eth0on << 'done'
#!/bin/sh
ip addr add 192.168.0.2/24 dev eth0
ip link set eth0 up
ip route add default via 192.168.0.1
done
chmod 0755 /mnt/sda7/var/tmp/eth0on

10. reboot (at grub menu select minimal-linux-new)

11. plug in an ethernet cable (if not already present)

12. execute eth0on

cd /var/tmp
./eth0on

13. ping something (ex. ping 8.8.8.8 or ping yahoo.com)

